Section 1:
1 L.D. 1364
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 INLAND FISHERIES AND WILDLIFE
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 887, L.D. 1364, “Resolve, Authorizing
10 a Study on the Impacts and Risks of Lead-based Ammunition”
11 Amend the resolve by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'Resolve, Directing the Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife to Evaluate
13 Efforts to Promote the Use of Non-lead Ammunition'
14 Amend the resolve by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
15 'Sec. 1. Evaluation. Resolved: That the Department of Inland Fisheries and
16 Wildlife, referred to in this resolve as "the department," is directed to conduct an evaluation
17 of its ongoing programs and efforts to educate the hunting community on the benefits
18 associated with the use of non-lead ammunition.
19 Sec. 2. Evaluation components. Resolved: That the evaluation described in
20 section 1 must take place over a 3-year period, beginning November 1, 2025, and must
21 include, but is not limited to, departmental surveys, a review of changes to other states'
22 laws related to lead-based ammunition used for hunting purposes and other data gathering
23 opportunities. The intent of the evaluation is to assess the ongoing effectiveness of the
24 department's efforts to educate the hunting community on the benefits associated with the
25 use of non-lead ammunition and promote enhanced educational efforts based on the results
26 of the evaluation. The department shall gather data described in this section on a periodic
27 basis. In addition to other information gathering efforts, the department shall include an
28 optional question on big game registration forms, both online and in-person, indicating
29 whether the ammunition used was or was not lead-based.
30 Sec. 3. Report. Resolved: That, no later than January 1, 2029, the department shall
31 submit a report with findings and recommendations based on the evaluation conducted
32 pursuant to this resolve to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having
33 jurisdiction over inland fisheries and wildlife matters. The committee may report out
34 legislation based on the report to the 134th Legislature in 2029.'
Page 1 - 132LR1441(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 887, L.D. 1364
1 Amend the resolve by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or
2 section number to read consecutively.
3 SUMMARY
44 This amendment replaces the resolve and changes the title. The amendment directs the
55 Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife to, over a 3-year period, beginning November
66 1, 2025, evaluate its ongoing programs and efforts to educate the hunting community on
77 the benefits associated with the use of non-lead ammunition. The evaluation must include
88 information on relevant departmental surveys and a review of changes to other states' laws
99 pertaining to lead-based ammunition used for hunting purposes with the goal of assessing
1100 the ongoing effectiveness of the department's efforts to educate the hunting community on
1111 the benefits associated with the use of non-lead ammunition. The department is directed to
1122 include an option question on big game registration forms, asking whether the ammunition
1133 used was lead-based or not. The department is directed to submit a report with evaluation
1144 findings and recommendations to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having
1155 jurisdiction over inland fisheries and wildlife matters no later than January 1, 2029. The
1166 committee may report out a bill based on the report to the 134th Legislature.
1177 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
1188 (See attached)
